{"title_page": "Alfons Weber", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|                name = Alfons Weber\n|               image =\n|            fullname = Alfons Weber\n|          birth_date = 1 August 1915\n|         birth_place = Switzerland\n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|              height = \n|            position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n|         currentclub = \n|          clubnumber = \n|         youthyears1 = \n|         youthclubs1 = \n|              years1 = 1933\u20131935\n|              clubs1 = [[FC Nordstern Basel|Nordstern Basel]]\n|               caps1 = 22\n|              goals1 = 6\n|              years2 = 1935\u20131936\n|              clubs2 = [[FC Bern]]\n|               caps2 = 26\n|              goals2 = 9\n|              years3 = 1936\u20131938\n|              clubs3 = [[FC Basel]]\n|               caps3 = 43\n|              goals3 = 11\n|              years4 = 1938\u20131944\n|              clubs4 = [[FC Lugano|Lugano]]\n|               caps4 = 129\n|              goals4 = 27\n|              years5 = 1945\u20131949\n|              clubs5 = [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]]\n|               caps5 = 73\n|              goals5 = 13\n|      nationalyears1 = 1937\u20131942\n|       nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]\n|       nationalcaps1 = 3\n|      nationalgoals1 = 0\n|       manageryears1 = \n|       managerclubs1 = \n|            pcupdate = \n|            ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Alfons Weber''' (born 1 August 1915; date of death unknown) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]]. He played as [[Forward (association football)|Striker]].\n\n== Club career ==\nWeber played his youth football with local club [[FC Nordstern Basel|Nordstern Basel]]. He advanced to their first team in 1933. He played two seasons with Nordstern and then moved on to play one season for [[FC Bern]].\n\nWeber joined [[FC Basel]]'s first team under team manager [[Heinz K\u00f6rner]] for their [[1936\u201337 FC Basel season|1936\u201337 season]]. After three test games he played his domestic league debut for his new club in away game on 30 August 1936 as Basel were defeated 0\u20131 by his old club Bern.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-bern-fcb 1936/37\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=28187 | title = FC Bern - FC Basel 1:0 (1:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club on 25 April 1937 in the home game at the [[Landhof]] against [[FC La Chaux-de-Fonds|La Chaux-de-Fonds]]. In fact he scored two as Basel won 3\u20132.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-lcdf 1936/37\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=28207 | title = FC Basel - FC La Chaux-de-Fonds 3:2 (2:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nBasel played a very poor and un-consistent season. Only thanks to four consecutive victories towards the end of the campain lifted the team to finish in joint second last position in the league table. Because [[FC La Chaux-de-Fonds|La Chaux-de-Fonds]] and Basel both had 20 points, they had to have a play-off against relegation. This was played in the [[Wankdorf Stadium]] in [[Bern]] on 13 June 1937. This ended goalless after 90 minutes. In over time La Chaux-de-Fonds took the lead, but Weber was able to equalise.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-play off 1 fcb-lcdf 1936/37\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=28211 | title = FC Basel - FC La Chaux-de-Fonds 1:1 n.V. (0:0, 0:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> The replay was played in the [[Stadion Neufeld]] in [[Bern]] on 20 June 1937 and ended in a 1\u20130 victory for Basel and so they prevented relegation at the last possible moment. \n\nThe following season Basel played a better and more consistent season under player-manager [[Fernand Jaccard]]. 22 league games in total, 12 of them ended with a victory, three ended in a draw and the team suffered seven defeats. With 27 points Basel ended the season in fourth position. In his two seasons Weber played a total of 61 games for Basel scoring a total of 21 goals. 43 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League|Nationalloga]], four in the [[Swiss Cup]] and 14 were friendly games. He scored 11 goals in the domestic league, two in the Cup and the others were scored during the test games.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-Alfons Weber\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=8965 | title = Alfons Weber - FCB-Statistik | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nWeber moved on and joined [[FC Lugano|Lugano]]. He stayed here for six seasons and this was Weber's most successful time. In the [[1940\u201341 Nationalliga|season 1940\u20131941]] Weber and Lugano were Swiss champions.<ref name=\"rsssf-Switzerland-1940/41\">{{cite web | first = | last = Erik Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit41.html | title = Switzerland 1940/41 | format = | work = | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> In the season 1942\u20131943 they reached the cup final and were runners-up in the league. In the season 1945\u20131946 Weber moved to [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]]. In the [[1947\u201348 Nationalliga A|season 1947\u20131948]] Weber won the championship with the club.<ref name=\"rsssf-Switzerland-1947/48\">{{cite web | first = | last = Erik Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit48.html | title = Switzerland 1947/48 | format = | work = | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He stayed in Bellinzona for four years before he ended his active career.\n\n== Club career ==\nWeber was called up for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] for the first time in 1937 by National team manager [[Karl Rappan]]. He played his debut for his country on 14 November 1937 in the test game against in Budapest against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as the hosts won by two goals to nil. Two years later he was called up again and played two more games for his country as the national team played in the winter camp against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].\n\n==Honours==\n;Lugano\n*[[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga]]: [[1940\u201341 Nationalliga|1940\u20131941]]\n\n;Bellinzona\n*[[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga A]]: [[1947\u201348 Nationalliga A|1947\u20131948]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Rotblau: Jahrbuch Saison 2017/2018. Publisher: FC Basel Marketing AG. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2189-1}}\n* Die ersten 125 Jahre. Publisher: Josef Zindel im Friedrich Reinhardt Verlag, Basel. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2305-5}}\n* [https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/home Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\" Homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weber, Alfons }}\n\n[[Category:FC Nordstern Basel players]]\n[[Category:FC Bern players]]\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:FC Lugano players]]\n[[Category:AC Bellinzona players]]\n[[Category:Swiss footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|                name = Alfons Weber\n|               image =\n|            fullname = Alfons Weber\n|          birth_date = 1 August 1915\n|         birth_place = Switzerland\n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|              height = \n|            position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n|         currentclub = \n|          clubnumber = \n|         youthyears1 = \n|         youthclubs1 = \n|              years1 = 1933\u20131935\n|              clubs1 = [[FC Nordstern Basel|Nordstern Basel]]\n|               caps1 = 22\n|              goals1 = 6\n|              years2 = 1935\u20131936\n|              clubs2 = [[FC Bern]]\n|               caps2 = 26\n|              goals2 = 9\n|              years3 = 1936\u20131938\n|              clubs3 = [[FC Basel]]\n|               caps3 = 43\n|              goals3 = 11\n|              years4 = 1938\u20131944\n|              clubs4 = [[FC Lugano|Lugano]]\n|               caps4 = 129\n|              goals4 = 27\n|              years5 = 1945\u20131949\n|              clubs5 = [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]]\n|               caps5 = 73\n|              goals5 = 13\n|      nationalyears1 = 1938\u20131942\n|       nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]\n|       nationalcaps1 = 3\n|      nationalgoals1 = 0\n|       manageryears1 = \n|       managerclubs1 = \n|            pcupdate = \n|            ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Alfons Weber''' (born 1 August 1915; date of death unknown) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]]. He played as [[Forward (association football)|Striker]].\n\n== Club career ==\nWeber played his youth football with local club [[FC Nordstern Basel|Nordstern Basel]]. He advanced to their first team in 1933. He played two seasons with Nordstern and then moved on to play one season for [[FC Bern]].\n\nWeber joined [[FC Basel]]'s first team under team manager [[Heinz K\u00f6rner]] for their [[1936\u201337 FC Basel season|1936\u201337 season]]. After three test games he played his domestic league debut for his new club in away game on 30 August 1936 as Basel were defeated 0\u20131 by his old club Bern.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-bern-fcb 1936/37\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=28187 | title = FC Bern - FC Basel 1:0 (1:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club on 25 April 1937 in the home game at the [[Landhof]] against [[FC La Chaux-de-Fonds|La Chaux-de-Fonds]]. In fact he scored two as Basel won 3\u20132.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-lcdf 1936/37\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=28207 | title = FC Basel - FC La Chaux-de-Fonds 3:2 (2:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nBasel played a very poor and un-consistent season. Only thanks to four consecutive victories towards the end of the campain lifted the team to finish in joint second last position in the league table. Because [[FC La Chaux-de-Fonds|La Chaux-de-Fonds]] and Basel both had 20 points, they had to have a play-off against relegation. This was played in the [[Wankdorf Stadium]] in [[Bern]] on 13 June 1937. This ended goalless after 90 minutes. In over time La Chaux-de-Fonds took the lead, but Weber was able to equalise.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-play off 1 fcb-lcdf 1936/37\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=28211 | title = FC Basel - FC La Chaux-de-Fonds 1:1 n.V. (0:0, 0:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> The replay was played in the [[Stadion Neufeld]] in [[Bern]] on 20 June 1937 and ended in a 1\u20130 victory for Basel and so they prevented relegation at the last possible moment. \n\nThe following season Basel played a better and more consistent season under player-manager [[Fernand Jaccard]]. 22 league games in total, 12 of them ended with a victory, three ended in a draw and the team suffered seven defeats. With 27 points Basel ended the season in fourth position. In his two seasons Weber played a total of 61 games for Basel scoring a total of 21 goals. 43 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League|Nationalloga]], four in the [[Swiss Cup]] and 14 were friendly games. He scored 11 goals in the domestic league, two in the Cup and the others were scored during the test games.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-Alfons Weber\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=8965 | title = Alfons Weber - FCB-Statistik | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nWeber moved on and joined [[FC Lugano|Lugano]]. He stayed here for six seasons and this was Weber's most successful time. In the [[1940\u201341 Nationalliga|season 1940\u20131941]] Weber and Lugano were Swiss champions.<ref name=\"rsssf-Switzerland-1940/41\">{{cite web | first = | last = Erik Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit41.html | title = Switzerland 1940/41 | format = | work = | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> In the season 1942\u20131943 they reached the cup final and were runners-up in the league. In the season 1945\u20131946 Weber moved to [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]]. In the [[1947\u201348 Nationalliga A|season 1947\u20131948]] Weber won the championship with the club.<ref name=\"rsssf-Switzerland-1947/48\">{{cite web | first = | last = Erik Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit48.html | title = Switzerland 1947/48 | format = | work = | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He stayed in Bellinzona for four years before he ended his active career.\n\n== Club career ==\nWeber was called up for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] for the first time in 1937 by National team manager [[Karl Rappan]]. He played his debut for his country on 14 November 1937 in the test game against in Budapest against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as the hosts won by two goals to nil. Two years later he was called up again and played two more games for his country as the national team played in the winter camp against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].\n\n==Honours==\n;Lugano\n*[[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga]]: [[1940\u201341 Nationalliga|1940\u20131941]]\n\n;Bellinzona\n*[[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga A]]: [[1947\u201348 Nationalliga A|1947\u20131948]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Rotblau: Jahrbuch Saison 2017/2018. Publisher: FC Basel Marketing AG. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2189-1}}\n* Die ersten 125 Jahre. Publisher: Josef Zindel im Friedrich Reinhardt Verlag, Basel. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2305-5}}\n* [https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/home Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\" Homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weber, Alfons }}\n\n[[Category:FC Nordstern Basel players]]\n[[Category:FC Bern players]]\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:FC Lugano players]]\n[[Category:AC Bellinzona players]]\n[[Category:Swiss footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfons_Weber"}
{"title_page": "Judy Hoffman (filmmaker)", "text_new": "[[File:Judy Hoffman.jpg|thumb|Judy Hoffman in 2016]]\n'''Judy Hoffman''' is an American [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] and arts activist based in [[Chicago]]. She graduated from [[Northwestern University]] with a [[Fine art|MFA]] and currently holds a faculty position at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = Our Mission|url = http://kartemquin.com/about/judy-hoffman|website = kartemquin.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref> Hoffman has played a major role in the development of [[Kartemquin Films]], a documentary filmmaking company founded in Chicago in 1966.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://cms.uchicago.edu/faculty/hoffman|title = Judy Hoffman|date = |accessdate = 18 October 2015|website = Division of Humanities at the University of Chicago Cinema and Media Studies|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Hoffman has worked with extensively with [[Kwakwaka'wakw|Kwakwaka\u2019wakw]], a [[First Nations|First Nation]] in [[British Columbia]], to produce films.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = http://dova.uchicago.edu/faculty/hoffman|title = Judy Hoffman|date = |accessdate = 18 October 2015|website = Department of Visual Arts the University of Chicago|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Most of Hoffman's work takes the form of documentaries focusing on Chicago and its development. Hoffman has brought activism to her films, and continues to show different facets of the city of Chicago.<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\n== Career ==\n\nHoffman has worked in the film industry for over 35 years. Her documentary style is influenced by her early work with small format video equipment, beginning with the [[Portapak]] and filming local Chicago communities. She was involved with the Alternative Television Movement in the early 1970s, documenting activism from the inside, especially to do with civil rights in Chicago<ref name=\":7\" />. \n\nAt the start, she worked for Jerry Temaner, one of the original founders of [[Kartemquin Films|Kartemquin films]], who ran a media production center at University of Illinois, Chicago. She met [[Jean Rouch]], French anthropologist and filmmaker, at the Ninth International Congress of Anthropological and Ethnological Sciences in 1973.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/01/18/jean-rouch-in-chicago-an-interview-with-judy-hoffman-and-gordon-quinn-of-kartemquin-films-part-one|title=Jean Rouch in Chicago: An interview with Judy Hoffman and Gordon Quinn of Kartemquin Films, part one|last=Sachs|first=Ben|website=Chicago Reader|language=en|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref> After she was assigned to be his assistant and show him around for his time in Chicago, they began work on a project surrounding race and jazz in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/01/23/jean-rouch-in-chicago-an-interview-with-judy-hoffman-and-gordon-quinn-of-kartemquin-films-part-three|title=Jean Rouch in Chicago: An interview with Judy Hoffman and Gordon Quinn of Kartemquin Films, part three|last=Sachs|first=Ben|website=Chicago Reader|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> Hoffman directly learned to shoot handheld and work with sound from Rouch, and conceptually became interested in [[cin\u00e9ma v\u00e9rit\u00e9]] and the idea of shared anthropology -- a collaborative approach to filmmaking which approaches the idea of documentary nontraditionally and often literally puts video equipment in the hands of the subjects<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berthe|first=Jamie|date=2018-07-03|title=Disruptive forms: the cinema of Jean Rouch|journal=Studies in French Cinema|volume=18|issue=3|pages=248\u2013251|doi=10.1080/14715880.2017.1383745|issn=1471-5880|doi-access=free}}</ref>. \n\nThis work brought her the connection to the Chicago film company [[Kartemquin Films]]<ref name=\":8\" />,  a collective focused on sharing knowledge and creating socialist-minded political work documenting Chicago<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rosenthal|first=Alan|title=The Documentary Conscience|publisher=University of California Press|year=1980|isbn=0-520-03932-7|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles, California|pages=401\u2013414}}</ref>. While at Kartemquin, Hoffman directed ''Golub,'' which went on to debut at the New York Film Festival. The mission of Kartemquin Films, and a guiding theme in Hoffman's work, is the principle of social inquiry, promoting social change through the medium of film.<ref name=\":3\" /> Hoffman still plays a major role at Kartemquin. \n\nHoffman's work with the Kwakwaka'wakw First Nation of British Columbia produced films and videotapes about reclaiming the tribe's culture. Through an introduction from an exchange between the [[U'mista Cultural Centre|U'Mista Cultural Center]] for the [[Kwakwaka\u02bcwakw|Kwakwaka'wakw]] First Nation of British Columbia and the [[Field Museum of Natural History|Field Museum]], Hoffman produced the award-winning ''Box of Treasures, 1983,'' a film documenting the efforts to repatriate cultural artifacts and create a cultural revival amid political strife. Out of connections from this film, Hoffman would return to Alert Bay to work with a video training program on the N'amgis Reserve, which led to an effort in the local community to create their own often educational documentary style work about their histories and rituals.<ref>Glass, A. (2006). ''Conspicuous consumption: An intercultural history of the kwakwaka'wakw hamat'sa'' (Order No. 3221951). Available from ProQuest Dissertations & Theses Global: The Humanities and Social Sciences Collection. (305279657). Retrieved from <nowiki>http://proxy.artic.edu/login?url=https://search-proquest-com.proxy.artic.edu/docview/305279657?accountid=26320</nowiki></ref>\n\nHoffman has worked as a producer and photographer for installations at the Smart Museum of Art and The Block Museum, among others.<ref name=\":3\" /> Judy Hoffman currently works at the [[University of Chicago]] as a Lecturer in the Department of Cinema and Media Studies and Department of Visual Arts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Significant Works ==\nIn 1996, Hoffman was Acting Director of The Documentary Center of [[Columbia College Chicago|Columbia College]] where along with Ronit Bezale, she developed ''Voices of Cabrini''. The film is about the destruction of public housing in Chicago.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2014, Hoffman worked as executive producer for ''70 Acres in Chicago: Cabrini Green'', which is the follow-up documentary to ''Voices of Cabrini''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.catherinecrouch.com/70-acres-in-chicago-2/|title=70 Acres In Chicago|date=2015-06-24|website=Catherine Crouch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\nHoffman has collaborated with [[Barbara Kopple]] on [[American Dream (film)|American Dream]] in 1990. Hoffman has worked with [[Michelle Citron]] on Mixed Greens in 2004.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nJudy Hoffman was the cinematographer for the films: [[Howard Zinn: You Can't Be Neutral on a Moving Train|''Howard Zinn: You Can't be Neutral on a Moving Train'']], ''Sacco and Vanzetti,'' and ''Nelson Algren:'' ''The End is Nothing,The Road is All.''<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0388979/|title=Judy Hoffman|website=IMDb|accessdate=2015-10-27}}</ref>\n\nHoffman's inclination towards documentary led her to film a behind the scenes look at Britney Spears, in a piece called ''Stages: Three Days in Mexico'', directed by [[Albert and David Maysles|Albert Maysles]] in 2002. A few years later, Hoffman was the videographer on Maysles' ''The Gates,'' which was a documentary on Jeanne Claude and Christo's Central Park installation. The documentary aired on HBO in 2006.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Awards and Recognition ==\nHoffman received the VOICE Media Activism Award from Chicago's Center for Community and Media in 1994. In 2004, Hoffman was awarded the Nelson Algren Committee Award for \"community activists making a significant contribution to Chicago life.\" <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://cms.uchicago.edu/faculty/hoffman|title=Judy Hoffman {{!}} Department of Cinema and Media Studies|website=cms.uchicago.edu|accessdate=2015-10-27}}</ref> \n\nHoffman serves on the Board's Advisory Committee to the Community TV Network, a non-profit organization in Chicago which works to promote community development among underrepresented youth through the educational tool and creative process of digital video production.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctvnetwork.org/about/board/|title=Board and Advisors|website=Community TV Network - CTVN|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> This committee is one of the many places where Hoffman has worked with her colleagues from Kartemquin films, including the founder [[Gordon Quinn]], and [[Peter Kuttner]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kartemquin.com/about/peter-kuttner|title=Peter Kuttner|website=kartemquin.com|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 Hoffman's film ''Stages: Three Days in Mexico,'' showed at the screening of the second season of Cinema 53, with a discussion series at the University of Chicago's Gray Center for Arts and Inquiry. The season series, \"Women Make Docs,\" continued Cinema 53's mission to present films made by women and people of color.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://southsideweekly.com/total-immersion-cinema-53/|title=Total Immersion at Cinema 53|date=2018-01-31|website=South Side Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Film\n!Year\n!Genre\n!Position\n|-\n|''Local 70''\n|1975\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer, Director, Editor<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''HSA #4''\n|1975\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://mediaburn.org/category/videomakers/judy-hoffman/|title=Judy Hoffman Archives - Media Burn Archive|website=Media Burn Archive|language=en|accessdate=2015-10-27}}</ref>\n|-\n|''HSA #1''\n|1979\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|''Seeing Red''\n|1983\n|Documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''The Last Pullman Car''\n|1983\n|Documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Box of Treasures''\n|1984\n|Short Documentary\n|Associate Producer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Women's Voices: The Gender Gap''\n|1984\n|Short documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''4 Tops live at the Park West''\n|1984\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|''Taylor Chain II: A Story of Collective Bargaining''\n|1984\n|Short\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''American Playhouse''\n|1984\n|TV series\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Golub''\n|1988\n|Documentary\n|Associate Producer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Time to Make That Change''\n|1992\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|''People for Community Recovery #1-8''\n|1993\n|Short\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|''The Good Life''\n|1995\n|TV series Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Frank Lloyd Wright''\n|1998\n|Documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Voices of Cabrini: Remaking Chicago's Public Housing''\n|1999\n|Short Documentary\n|Executive Producer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediaburn.org/video/voices-of-cabrini/|title=Media Burn Archive \u2013 Voices of Cabrini: Remaking Chicago's Public Housing|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Nova''\n|2001\n|TV series and documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Stages: Three Days in Mexico - Britney Spears''\n|2002\n|Documentary\n|Cinematographer,\n\nDirector<ref name=\":5\" /> \n|-\n|''Golub: Late Works Are the Catastrophes''\n|2004\n|Documentary\n|Photographer,\nAssociate Producer<ref name=\":5\" /> \n|-\n|''[[Howard Zinn: You Can't Be Neutral on a Moving Train]]''\n|2004\n|Documentary\n|Cinematographer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''A Day on the Force: Women's Professional Tackle Football''\n|2004\n|Documentary\n|Cinematographer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Sacco and Vanzetti''\n|2006\n|Documentary\n|Videographer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''The Gates''\n|2007\n|Documentary\n|Videographer<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mayslesfilms.com/film/the-gates/|title=The Gates|date=2014-02-18|website=MAYSLES FILMS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|''In My Room: The Inner Life of Teen Girls''\n|2007\n|Documentary\n|Cinematographer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''70 Acres in Chicago:Cabrini Green''\n|2014\n|Documentary\n|Executive Producer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Nelson Algren: The End Is Nothing, the Road Is All...''\n|2015\n|Documentary\n|Camera Operator, Cinematographer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Leftovers''\n|2017\n|Documentary\n|Videographer<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/pages/c962.shtml|title=WOMEN MAKE MOVIES {{!}} Lives: Visible/Leftovers|website=www.wmm.com|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n|}\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoffman, Judy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:American documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Judy Hoffman.jpg|thumb|Judy Hoffman in 2016]]\n'''Judy Hoffman''' is an American [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]] and arts activist based in [[Chicago]]. She graduated from [[Northwestern University]] with a [[Fine art|MFA]] and currently holds a faculty position at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = Our Mission|url = http://kartemquin.com/about/judy-hoffman|website = kartemquin.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref> Hoffman has played a major role in the development of [[Kartemquin Films]], a documentary filmmaking company founded in Chicago in 1966.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://cms.uchicago.edu/faculty/hoffman|title = Judy Hoffman|date = |accessdate = 18 October 2015|website = Division of Humanities at the University of Chicago Cinema and Media Studies|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Hoffman has worked with extensively with [[Kwakwaka'wakw|Kwakwaka\u2019wakw]], a [[First Nations|First Nation]] in [[British Columbia]], to produce films.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = http://dova.uchicago.edu/faculty/hoffman|title = Judy Hoffman|date = |accessdate = 18 October 2015|website = Department of Visual Arts the University of Chicago|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Most of Hoffman's work takes the form of documentaries focusing on Chicago and its development. Hoffman has brought activism to her films, and continues to show different facets of the city of Chicago.<ref name=\":3\" /> She has collaborated with many filmmakers, including [[Jean Rouch]], [[Barbara Kopple]], and [[Albert and David Maysles|Albert Maysles]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Career ==\n\nHoffman has worked in the film industry for over 35 years. Her documentary style is influenced by her early work with small format video equipment, beginning with the [[Portapak]] and filming local Chicago communities. She was involved with the Alternative Television Movement in the early 1970s, documenting activism from the inside, especially to do with civil rights in Chicago<ref name=\":7\" />. \n\nAt the start, she worked for Jerry Temaner, one of the original founders of [[Kartemquin Films|Kartemquin films]], who ran a media production center at University of Illinois, Chicago. She met [[Jean Rouch]], French anthropologist and filmmaker, at the Ninth International Congress of Anthropological and Ethnological Sciences in 1973.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/01/18/jean-rouch-in-chicago-an-interview-with-judy-hoffman-and-gordon-quinn-of-kartemquin-films-part-one|title=Jean Rouch in Chicago: An interview with Judy Hoffman and Gordon Quinn of Kartemquin Films, part one|last=Sachs|first=Ben|website=Chicago Reader|language=en|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref> After she was assigned to be his assistant and show him around for his time in Chicago, they began work on a project surrounding race and jazz in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/01/23/jean-rouch-in-chicago-an-interview-with-judy-hoffman-and-gordon-quinn-of-kartemquin-films-part-three|title=Jean Rouch in Chicago: An interview with Judy Hoffman and Gordon Quinn of Kartemquin Films, part three|last=Sachs|first=Ben|website=Chicago Reader|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> Hoffman directly learned to shoot handheld and work with sound from Rouch, and conceptually became interested in [[cin\u00e9ma v\u00e9rit\u00e9]] and the idea of shared anthropology -- a collaborative approach to filmmaking which approaches the idea of documentary nontraditionally and often literally puts video equipment in the hands of the subjects<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berthe|first=Jamie|date=2018-07-03|title=Disruptive forms: the cinema of Jean Rouch|journal=Studies in French Cinema|volume=18|issue=3|pages=248\u2013251|doi=10.1080/14715880.2017.1383745|issn=1471-5880|doi-access=free}}</ref>. \n\nThis work brought her the connection to the Chicago film company [[Kartemquin Films]]<ref name=\":8\" />,  a collective focused on sharing knowledge and creating socialist-minded political work documenting Chicago<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rosenthal|first=Alan|title=The Documentary Conscience|publisher=University of California Press|year=1980|isbn=0-520-03932-7|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles, California|pages=401\u2013414}}</ref>. While at Kartemquin, Hoffman directed ''Golub,'' which went on to debut at the New York Film Festival. The mission of Kartemquin Films, and a guiding theme in Hoffman's work, is the principle of social inquiry, promoting social change through the medium of film.<ref name=\":3\" /> Hoffman still plays a major role at Kartemquin. \n\nHoffman's work with the Kwakwaka'wakw First Nation of British Columbia produced films and videotapes about reclaiming the tribe's culture. Through an introduction from an exchange between the [[U'mista Cultural Centre|U'Mista Cultural Center]] for the [[Kwakwaka\u02bcwakw|Kwakwaka'wakw]] First Nation of British Columbia and the [[Field Museum of Natural History|Field Museum]], Hoffman produced the award-winning ''Box of Treasures, 1983,'' a film documenting the efforts to repatriate cultural artifacts and create a cultural revival amid political strife. Out of connections from this film, Hoffman would return to Alert Bay to work with a video training program on the N'amgis Reserve, which led to an effort in the local community to create their own often educational documentary style work about their histories and rituals.<ref>Glass, A. (2006). ''Conspicuous consumption: An intercultural history of the kwakwaka'wakw hamat'sa'' (Order No. 3221951). Available from ProQuest Dissertations & Theses Global: The Humanities and Social Sciences Collection. (305279657). Retrieved from <nowiki>http://proxy.artic.edu/login?url=https://search-proquest-com.proxy.artic.edu/docview/305279657?accountid=26320</nowiki></ref>\n\nHoffman has worked as a producer and photographer for installations at the Smart Museum of Art and The Block Museum, among others.<ref name=\":3\" /> Judy Hoffman currently works at the [[University of Chicago]] as a Lecturer in the Department of Cinema and Media Studies and Department of Visual Arts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Significant Works ==\nIn 1996, Hoffman was Acting Director of The Documentary Center of [[Columbia College Chicago|Columbia College]] where along with Ronit Bezale, she developed ''Voices of Cabrini''. The film is about the destruction of public housing in Chicago.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2014, Hoffman worked as executive producer for ''70 Acres in Chicago: Cabrini Green'', which is the follow-up documentary to ''Voices of Cabrini''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.catherinecrouch.com/70-acres-in-chicago-2/|title=70 Acres In Chicago|date=2015-06-24|website=Catherine Crouch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\nHoffman has collaborated with [[Barbara Kopple]] on [[American Dream (film)|American Dream]] in 1990. Hoffman has worked with [[Michelle Citron]] on Mixed Greens in 2004.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nJudy Hoffman was the cinematographer for the films: [[Howard Zinn: You Can't Be Neutral on a Moving Train|''Howard Zinn: You Can't be Neutral on a Moving Train'']], ''Sacco and Vanzetti,'' and ''Nelson Algren:'' ''The End is Nothing,The Road is All.''<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0388979/|title=Judy Hoffman|website=IMDb|accessdate=2015-10-27}}</ref>\n\nHoffman's inclination towards documentary led her to film a behind the scenes look at Britney Spears, in a piece called ''Stages: Three Days in Mexico'', directed by [[Albert and David Maysles|Albert Maysles]] in 2002. A few years later, Hoffman was the videographer on Maysles' ''The Gates,'' which was a documentary on Jeanne Claude and Christo's Central Park installation. The documentary aired on HBO in 2006.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Awards and Recognition ==\nHoffman received the VOICE Media Activism Award from Chicago's Center for Community and Media in 1994. In 2004, Hoffman was awarded the Nelson Algren Committee Award for \"community activists making a significant contribution to Chicago life.\" <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://cms.uchicago.edu/faculty/hoffman|title=Judy Hoffman {{!}} Department of Cinema and Media Studies|website=cms.uchicago.edu|accessdate=2015-10-27}}</ref> \n\nHoffman serves on the Board's Advisory Committee to the Community TV Network, a non-profit organization in Chicago which works to promote community development among underrepresented youth through the educational tool and creative process of digital video production.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ctvnetwork.org/about/board/|title=Board and Advisors|website=Community TV Network - CTVN|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> This committee is one of the many places where Hoffman has worked with her colleagues from Kartemquin films, including the founder [[Gordon Quinn]], and [[Peter Kuttner]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kartemquin.com/about/peter-kuttner|title=Peter Kuttner|website=kartemquin.com|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018 Hoffman's film ''Stages: Three Days in Mexico,'' showed at the screening of the second season of Cinema 53, with a discussion series at the University of Chicago's Gray Center for Arts and Inquiry. The season series, \"Women Make Docs,\" continued Cinema 53's mission to present films made by women and people of color.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://southsideweekly.com/total-immersion-cinema-53/|title=Total Immersion at Cinema 53|date=2018-01-31|website=South Side Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Film\n!Year\n!Genre\n!Position\n|-\n|''Local 70''\n|1975\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer, Director, Editor<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''HSA #4''\n|1975\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://mediaburn.org/category/videomakers/judy-hoffman/|title=Judy Hoffman Archives - Media Burn Archive|website=Media Burn Archive|language=en|accessdate=2015-10-27}}</ref>\n|-\n|''HSA #1''\n|1979\n|Short Documentary\n|Producer<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|''Seeing Red''\n|1983\n|Documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''The Last Pullman Car''\n|1983\n|Documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Box of Treasures''\n|1984\n|Short Documentary\n|Associate Producer<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''Women's Voices: The Gender Gap''\n|1984\n|Short documentary\n|Camera assistant<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|''4 Tops live at the Park West''\n|1984\n|Short Documentary\n|